{"questionId":"21326","questionHtml":"<p>Tower <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>T1</mtext></math> has coordinates <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>)</mo></math>.</p>\n<p>Find the gradient of the edge of the Voronoi diagram between towers <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>T1</mtext></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>T2</mtext></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>correct use of gradient formula&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em>e.g.</em>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>-</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p>taking negative reciprocal of <strong>their</strong> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math> (at any point)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>edge gradient <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;<em><strong><br>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"21326","referenceCode":"21M.1.SL.TZ1.5c","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Tower T1 has coordinates (-13, 3). Find the gradient of the edge of the Voronoi diagram between towers T1 and T2.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.6—Voronoi diagrams"],"m